## Non Homogeneous Linear Equations

$$y'' + p(x)y'+q(x)y=f(x)$$

::: {.fragment}
$f(x)\neq 0$
:::

::: {.fragment}
**Examples:**

1. Forced Harmonic Oscillator with damping: $$\boxed{m x'' + b x' + k x = F(t)}$$
2. Electrical circuits:  $$\boxed{Lq''+Rq'+(1/C) q = V(t) }$$
:::



## Theorem Existence & Uniqueness

::: {.callout-note}
## Theorem
::: {#thm-Exi-Uniq}
## Existence & Uniqueness
Suppose $p,q,f$ are continuous on $(a,b)$.
Let $x_0\in(a,b),\,k_0,k_1\in\mathbb{R}$

Then the initial value problem $$y''+p(x)y'+q(x)y=f(x),\qquad y(x_0)=k_  0,\quad y'(x_0)=k_1$$
has a unique solution on $(a,b)$
:::
:::


## The Complementary Equation {.scrollable}

::: {.callout-note}
## Definition

$$y''+p(x)y'+q(x)y=f(x)$$ has a `complementary equation`

$$y''+p(x)y'+q(x)y=0$$

:::

## General Sol for Non-Homogeneous{.scrollable}

::: {.callout-note}
## Theorem

::: {#thm-Gral-Sol-Comp-Eq}
## General Solution and complementary equation

Suppose $p,q,f$ are continuous on $(a,b)$.

Let $y_p$ be a particular solution to

$$y'' + p(x)y'+q(x)y=f(x)$${#eq-GS2OLNH}

Let $\{y_1,y_2\}$ be a fundamental set of solutions to the complementary equation
$$y'' + p(x)y'+q(x)y=0$${#eq-comp}
Then the general solution to @eq-GS2OLNH is

$$y=c_1y_1+c_2y_2+y_p$$
:::

:::


::: {.callout-caution collapse="true"}
### Proof 

:::{.proof}
:::{.fragment}
$$y'=c_1y_1'+c_2y_2'+y_p'$$
$$y''=c_1y_1''+c_2y_2''+y_p''$$
:::

:::{.fragment}
$\Rightarrow$ plug into the 2OLNH (@eq-2OLNH):

\begin{align}
(c_1y_1''+c_2y_2''+y_p'') +&\\ p(x)(c_1y_1'+c_2y_2'+y_p')+\\
q(x)(c_1y_1+c_2y_2+y_p)&\\
&=f(x)
\end{align}
:::

:::{.fragment}
\begin{align}
c_1(y_1''+p(x)y_1'+q(x)y_1)&\\ c_2(y_2''+p(x)y_2'+q(x)y_2)+\\
y_p''+p(x)y_p'+q(x)y_p&\\
&=f(x)
\end{align}
$$\square$$
:::
:::
:::

::: {.callout-tip}
### Example {.scrollable}

Solve $$y''+y=1,\qquad y(0)=2,\quad y'(0)=7$$

::: {.callout-caution collapse="true"}
## Solution

::: {.fragment}
**Complementary Equation:**
$$\Rightarrow y''+y=0$$
$$r^2+1=0\Rightarrow r_{1,2}=0\pm 1i$$
$$y_i=c_1\cos x +c_2\sin x$$
:::

::: {.fragment}

**Particular Solution:**
(By inspection$\rightarrow$ techniques to follow)
$$y=1$$
:::

::: {.fragment}
**General Solution:**
$$y=c_1\cos x +c_2\sin x+1$$
:::

:::{.fragment}
**Initial Conditions:**
$$y(0)=2\Rightarrow c_1+1=2\Rightarrow c_1=1$$
$$y'=-\sin x +c_2\cos x\Rightarrow y'(0)=7\Rightarrow c_2=7$$
:::

:::{.fragment}
**Final Solution:**

$$\boxed{y=\cos x+ 7\sin x +1}$$
:::
:::
:::


::: {.callout-tip}
### Example 2 {.scrollable}

1. Find the general solution of $$y'' ŌłÆ 2y' + y = ŌłÆ3 ŌłÆ x + x^2$$
2. Solve the initial value problem $$y'' ŌłÆ 2y' + y = ŌłÆ3 ŌłÆ x + x^2,\qquad y(0) = ŌłÆ2,\quad y'(0) = 1$$

::: {.callout-caution collapse="true"}
## Solution 1

Let's find first the solution for the homogeneous, where the characteristic equation is:

$$r^2-2r+1=0$$
Then $$r_{1,2}=\frac{+2\pm\sqrt{4-4}}{2}=1=m\rightarrow \boxed{m=-p/2=1}$$

Therefore:

$$y=c_1e^{x}+c_2xe^{x}+y_p$$
Now the goal is a particular for the non homogeneous:

$$y'' ŌłÆ 2y' + y = ŌłÆ3 ŌłÆ x + x^2$$
**Guess:**

Let's choose $y_p$ as a polynomial of order 2, so the LHS have the same order of RHS:

$$\boxed{y_p=Ax^2+Bx+C}\rightarrow y'_p=2Ax+B\rightarrow y''_p=2A$$
and see what are the conditions the constants need to satisfy:

$$2A-2(2Ax+B)+(Ax^2+Bx+C)=ŌłÆ3 ŌłÆ x + x^2$$
Grouping:

$$(2A-2B+C) + (-4A+B)x +Ax^2=ŌłÆ3 ŌłÆ x + x^2$$
Therefore:

\begin{align}
2A-2B+C&=-3\\
-4A+B&=-1\\
A&=1\\
\end{align}

$$\Rightarrow \boxed{A=1}\rightarrow \boxed{B=3}\rightarrow \boxed{C=1}$$

Then a particular soln for the non-homogeneous:

$$\boxed{y_p= x^2+3x+1}$$

Then the general solution for the non-homogeneous is:

$$\boxed{\boxed{y=c_1e^{x}+c_2xe^{x}+x^2+3x+1}}$$
:::


::: {.callout-caution collapse="true"}
## Solution 2

$$y(0) = ŌłÆ2,\quad y'(0) = 1$$
$$y=c_1e^{x}+c_2xe^{x}+x^2+3x+1$$
i.c.1:
$$-2=c_1+0+0+0+1\Rightarrow \boxed{c_1=-3}$$
i.c.2:

$$y=-3e^{x}+c_2xe^{x}+x^2+3x+1$$
$$\Rightarrow$$ 
$$y'=-3e^{x}+c_2e^{x}+c_2xe^{x}+2x+3$$

$$1=-3+c_2+c_2\cdot 0+2\cdot 0+3$$
Then $$1=-3+c_2+3\rightarrow \boxed{c_2=1}$$

Finally, the unique solution for this initial conditions is:

$$\boxed{y=-3e^{x}+xe^{x}+x^2+3x+1}$$

:::
:::


## Particular solution as a combination of particulars{.scrollable}

::: {.callout-note}
## Theorem

::: {#thm-part-solns}
## Particular Solutions

If $y_{p_1}$ is a particular solution of

$$y'' +p(x)y' + q(x)y =f_1(x)$$
and $y_{p_2}$ is a particular solution of

$$y'' +p(x)y' + q(x)y =f_2(x)$$
Then $\boxed{y_p=y_{p_1}+y_{p_2}}$ is a particular solution of

$$y''+p(x)y'+q(x)y=f_1(x)+f_2(x)$$
:::


::: {.callout-caution collapse="true"}
### Proof 

:::{.proof}

$$y''+p(x)y'+q(x)y\stackrel{?}{=}$$
$$(y_{p_1}''+y_{p_2}'')+p(x)(y_{p_1}'+y_{p_2}')+q(x)(y_{p_1}+y_{p_2})\stackrel{?}{=}$$
$$(y_{p_1}''+p(x)y_{p_1}'+q(x)y_{p_1})+(y_{p_2}''+p(x)y_{p_2}'+q(x)y_{p_2})\stackrel{?}{=}$$
$$=f_1(x)+f_2(x)$$
$$\square$$
:::
:::
:::

